1. Introduction ¶

GitHub link: https://github.com/machristensen1/student-perf-uci-ml/

In this project, we'll be taking a look at how various unsupervised models perform with respect to clustering seeds into different wheat species using data from the following dataset: https://archive.ics.uci.edu/dataset/236/seeds

We'll be taking a look at K-Means clustering and Agglomerative (Hierarchical) Clustering and how it compares against the supervised K Nearest Neighbors algorithm.

The examined group comprised kernels belonging to three different varieties of wheat: Kama, Rosa and Canadian, 70 elements each, randomly selected forthe experiment. High quality visualization of the internal kernel structure was detected using a soft X-ray technique. It is non-destructive and considerably cheaper than other more sophisticated imaging techniques like scanning microscopy or laser technology. The images were recorded on 13x18 cm X-ray KODAK plates. Studies were conducted using combine harvested wheat grain originating from experimental fields, explored at the Institute of Agrophysics of the Polish Academy of Sciences in Lublin. The data set can be used for the tasks of classification and cluster analysis. To construct the data, seven geometric parameters of wheat kernels were measured:

The indepedent variables of interest are:

  1. area A,
  2. perimeter P,
  3. compactness C = 4piA/P^2,
  4. length of kernel,
  5. width of kernel,
  6. asymmetry coefficient
  7. length of kernel groove.

Collinearity/Correlation¶

Although many of the variables appear to be highly correlated, we are mainly concerned about maximizing our predictive power. The models we are using do not lose that much fidelity from correlated/collinear data. Length and Width are likely the most important factors in terms of model performance since the other factors are mathematically proportional to Length and Width (e.g. Area, Perimeter, Compactness).

Analysis¶

  • All models seem to perform fairly similarly, with KNN being the worst peforming of the three.
  • KMeans performed the best out of the three, likely because the model has three distinct clusters where most metrics don't appear to be sensitive to initial conditions. Agglomerative clustering performed similarly - both clustering algorithms are based on distance metrics.
  • KNN performed the worst, but still reasonably well. There isn't much noise in the data, so 1-neighbor clustering was able to give us fairly good model performance.
  • It appears that Kama and Canadian are the most easily confused species in all three models.that we used. We can see this both graphically with how much overlap there is between these two grain types for many of their factors, as well as from the confusion matrices for each of the models.

Discussion & Conclusion ¶

The parent paper utilized a different clustering algorithm called the Complete Gradient Clustering Algorithm and was able to achieve an accuracy of about 92%. What is interesting about this algorithm is that it did not require the number of clusters to be identified as a hyperparameter before modeling, and still performed better than my application of KMeans clustering.

Classification success for original paper:

We could likely improve model performance by utilizing PCA/NMF to reduce the dimensionality of the dataset before applying our models.

Additionally, the CGCA algorithm was able to identify what they called "one-element clusters" which are essentially outliers in our data. While they didn't remove any outliers in the original paper, it is possible that we could have improved the performance of our models by removing outliers in the data.
